    "content": "<h2>Why clean form beats 100 sloppy reps</h2>\n<p>Push-ups are an underrated full-body exercise — deceptively simple, with dozens of moving parts. Fifty sloppy reps train compensatory patterns and tendon overload. Twenty clean reps build strength that transfers. The seven mistakes below show up in nearly every beginner video, and three of them eventually cost you a shoulder.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 1: Sagging hips — the unstable middle</h2>\n<p>By far the most common error. When the hips drop below the line from shoulders to heels, the lumbar spine becomes a flexing bridge. It doesn&#39;t hurt right away, but it adds up. The cause is usually a weak core that lets go under load.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Before lowering, brace the abs as if expecting a punch. The brace must hold until the end of the set. If you lose it, the set is over — regardless of the planned reps.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 2: Flared elbows — shoulder-killer number one</h2>\n<p>The classic &quot;T-position&quot;: elbows splayed 90° from the torso. Looks dramatic, but it drives the humeral head straight into the acromion. Repeat that often enough and subacromial impingement is on the way.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Elbows should track at roughly 45° to the torso during the descent. Imagine you&#39;re trying to graze your hips with the elbows. Hands stay under the shoulders or slightly wider — never far out.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 3: Half reps — the quiet self-deception</h2>\n<p>Ego reps where the chest reverses 8 inches above the floor. Sounds great as a 50-rep stat; leaves out the lower half of the strength curve, which is exactly where the growth stimulus lives.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Chest touches the floor (or comes within an inch). If that&#39;s not possible, regress to elevated hands — windowsill, chair, stair — until you can lower fully. Eight clean reps beat twenty half ones every time.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 4: Head up — neck instead of core</h2>\n<p>Under exertion the head reflexively tilts back. The cervical spine extends, the upper traps jump in, and after 50 reps your neck hurts more than your chest.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Eyes about half a meter (1.5 ft) in front of your hands on the floor. Head stays in line with the spine — as if balancing a cup on the back of your skull.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 5: Tempo roulette — fast down, slow up</h2>\n<p>Catching the floor and bouncing up. But the eccentric phase (the descent) is the primary hypertrophy driver. Skip it and you leave 40% of the effect on the table.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> 2 seconds down, brief pause at the bottom, controlled press up. Only after you&#39;ve mastered tempo 1-1-1-0 should you graduate to explosive push-ups.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 6: Holding your breath — the invisible brake</h2>\n<p>Valsalva pressing during the push raises intrathoracic pressure and can trigger lightheadedness. Across longer sets, force production also suffers.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Inhale on the descent, exhale on the press. A short brace is okay during max attempts, but don&#39;t sustain it across multiple reps. More on this in our <a href=\"/en/blog/pushup-breathing\">breathing technique article</a>.</p>\n<h2>Mistake 7: Too much too soon — volume over quality</h2>\n<p>&quot;100 push-ups a day&quot; sounds disciplined but is, for 95% of beginners, the fastest path to shoulder inflammation. Connective tissue and tendons adapt slower than muscle.</p>\n<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Increase weekly volume by no more than 10%. If you hit 100 reps last week, target 110 — not 200. Patience beats heroism.</p>\n<h2>The 5-minute self-diagnosis</h2>\n<p>Set your phone aside and film a set of 10 reps. Watch the clip twice: once from the side (hip line, depth), once from behind (elbow angle, shoulder position). Within 30 seconds you&#39;ll see which of the seven mistakes dominates. Repair one per training week — not all at once.</p>\n<aside class=\"plan-cta\">\n  <h3>Form clean? Now's the time for volume</h3>\n  <p>\n    With your technique solid, you're ready for structured volume. The\n    <a href=\"/en/training-plans/recruit-6w\">6-week buildup plan</a> takes you from 0 to 100 clean\n    reps using progressive overload, not crash programming.\n  </p>\n</aside>",
